Oboko Bwane (Magega Nero Ekoonia Motu) is a storytelling anthem inspired by real-life situations in our society.

The song tells a mahari (bride price / okomaana chiombe) story through a modern lens. It starts in the club men enjoying life, buying drinks, dancing, and living in the moment. In the middle of the fun, reality hits: someone remembers they were supposed to go pay bride price. That’s where the line “natotinda mbaka ng’ende gochi komaana” comes from. Time is running, decisions are rushed, and the journey begins.

When they arrive home, everything falls apart. Anger, persuasion, and confusion take over  until the deeper truth is revealed: manipulation, drugs, lust, shortcuts, and temptation. This is where “agotumeka egetenyako (kamothe, kababa, amaebi)” and “Magega Nero Ekoonia Motu” come in  metaphors showing how desire and easy paths can destroy responsibility, families, and values.

This is not lazy music.
It’s a song that demands thought.

Oboko Bwane speaks boldly about real issues affecting our communities today:

Drug abuse and its impact on marriages

Alcohol and bar culture among men and women

Reckless spending driven by pressure and pleasure

Lust and temptation

Manipulation in clubs (kababa, kamothe, amaebi, michele)

Men abandoning families for short-term pleasure

Married people chasing bodies (Ebwobi) without considering consequences


These are stories we see and hear every day  families breaking apart and responsibilities forgotten in the name of enjoyment.
